---------------------------------------------------------------------------
WORLD ROUND-UP
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

IRAN: New crackdown on universities

The Iranian government has said it will restrict the number of students
admitted to humanities programmes at universities, Radio Free Europe and
Radio Liberty=92s Radio Farda reports. The announcement was made on 25 Augu=
st
by Abolfazl Hassani, director of the government=92s Office of Development of
Higher Education.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100829095205295

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

ISRAEL: Professors protest =91political pressures=92

Israeli professors representing the faculties of all of Israel=92s seven
research universities have publicly denounced =93political pressures brought
to bear on universities recently, which are tantamount to blatant
interference in academic freedom=94, writes Matthew Kalman for The Chronicle
of Higher Education.
More on the University World News site :
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010082722575439

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: Phd quantity surpasses quality

With a rapid increase in the number of Chinese graduates enrolling in PhD
programmes in the past decade, it seems the quality of education doctoral
students receive is falling short, writes He Dan for the official agency
Xinhua.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225656580

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

ASIA: Regional universities agree on network deal

Eleven universities in Cambodia, Laos and Viet Nam signed an agreement last
week during a University Presidents=92 Conference in Ho Chi Minh City,
Vietnam, to develop a collaborative network in the region, reports Viet Nam
News.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100829100114341

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

AUSTRALIA: Latin American students wooed

During the past six years, Australia has had rapid success in recruiting
students from a relatively new market: Latin America, writes Janaki Kremmer
for The Chronicle of Higher Education. Since 2004, enrolment of students
from the region has risen from 7,000 to 34,000.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225607657

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Students fuel rise in immigration

Official statistics show that a surge in the number of foreign students
studying in the UK helped drive up net migration by 20% last year, reports
Channel 4 News.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225458518

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Study questions science-economic growth link

An academic believes he has found evidence to refute the argument that
increased university provision of science, technology, engineering and
mathematics (Stem) subjects is needed to aid the economy, writes John
Morgan for Inside Higher Ed.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225402592

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

N IGERIA: Retirement age for professors rises to 70

Professors will now stay longer in universities after N igeria=92s federal
government pushed back the national mandatory retirement age from 65 to 70,
reports Next. Non-academic staff also received a further five years after
the government increased their retirement age to 65.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225301559

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MOZAMBIQUE: New regulations for higher education

The Mozambican government has approved new regulations on the licensing and
functioning of higher education institutions which collectively deal with
more than 70,000 students, reports AllAfrica.com.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225204128

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

TAIWAN: Universities score poorly on student rights=20

Seventy percent of universities included in a nationwide student rights
evaluation received failing scores, reflecting a general disregard for
student rights in Taiwan, reports the The China Post.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225104167

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SOUTH AFRICA: Whites-only fund fights to stay white

A high court ruling which made an educational fund for poor white girls
available to girls from all races was disputed in the Supreme Court of
Appeal, reports the South African Press Association.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827225003258

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

INDIA: State sets sights on first vocational university

The Maharashtra state government is considering setting up a vocational
university that would be the first of its kind in the country, said
minister for higher and technical education Rajesh Tope, reports The Times
of India.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827224906891

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CANADA: Rented textbook option gains ground

Students at Carleton University in Ottawa will have the option of renting
their textbooks from the beginning of the upcoming semester, reports CBC
News. The school=92s bookstore is one of six across Canada trying out
Rent-A-Text, which has been a successful programme in the United States,
where it has helped to reduce student study costs.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100827224805992



