a, sans-serif; font-size: 11pt; color: #FFFFFF;"><b>SPECIAL REPORT</b></spa=
n></td></tr></table></font><br>=93Never before have there been so many soci=
al scientists in the world =96 many more than the 200,000 population of Mar=
garet Mead=92s famous Samoa. Never before have the social sciences been so =
influential,=94 writes Gudmund Hernes, President of the International Socia=
l Science Council, in the preface to the <I>World Social Science Report 201=
0: Knowledge divides</I>. Published by Unesco, the 400-page report has 10 c=
hapters covering a wide range of issues confronting the social sciences and=
 their role in countries across all continents.<BR>
<BR>
In a foreword Irina Bokova, Unesco Director-General, says the report is the=
 first =93thorough overview of this important field in more than a decade=
=94 and is the result of the work of hundreds of professional social scient=
ists. Bokova says Unesco, =93with its emphasis on the management of social =
transformation=94, is concerned that the social sciences should be put to u=
se to improve human well-being and to respond to global challenges.<BR>
<BR>
The following articles by <B><I>GEOFF MASLEN</I></B> are drawn from various=
 chapters in the report.<BR>
<br><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt; color: #003366"><b>GLOBAL: Worlds apart=
 but on same map?</b></span><br>In spite of the impact social scientists ha=
ve had around the world, Gudmund Hernes says humans face crises that tax th=
eir understanding and their capacity to cope. The President of the Internat=
ional Social Science Council describes the influence of social science as a=
 =93mixed blessing=94 and says social scientists=92 foresight has been poor=
 at key junctures in recent times.<br><a href=3D"http://www.universityworld=
news.com/article.php?story=3D20100828051852222" style=3D"font-size: 8pt; co=
lor: #6699CC" target=3D"_src"><font color=3D"#6699CC"><b>Full report on the=
 University World News site</b></font></a><br><br><span style=3D"font-size:=
 10pt; color: #003366"><b>GLOBAL: Social sciences brain drain or gain?</b><=
/span><br>Social scientists migrate from the main academic centres to the p=
eriphery to teach, export their skills or do research and gather data. In t=
he opposite direction, talented young social scientists tend to leave a per=
ipheral position to go to academic centres to be trained or work with the m=
ost eminent scholars, says Laurent Jeanpierre, a professor of political sci=
ence at the University of Paris-8 Saint-Denis.<br><a href=3D"http://www.uni=
versityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100828051754887" style=3D"font-s=
