UK: Challenging ruling mantras of higher education</b></span><br><I>John Hi=
ggins*</I><BR>
There is a special kind of British humour that is very good at locating the=
 absurd in everyday life. It draws our attention to much of what we take fo=
r granted just by tone of voice or the raising of an eyebrow. Either of the=
se can be enough to effectively place scare quotes around a clich=E9; or dr=
aw our critical attention to something, and make us laugh at the sudden abs=
urdity of what once seemed authoritative.   <br><a href=3D"http://www.unive=
rsityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100828205244802" style=3D"font-siz=
e: 8pt; color: #6699CC" target=3D"_src"><font color=3D"#6699CC"><b>Full rep=
ort on the University World News site</b></font></a><br><br><span style=3D"=
font-size: 10pt; color: #003366"><b>JAPAN: Top universities sharpen interna=
tional focus</b></span><br><I>Michinari Hamaguchi*</I><BR>
 Japanese society is undergoing transformative changes amidst a wave of IT =
growth and globalisation. Even the =91once-in-a-century=92 recession of two=
 years ago seems merely a ripple in this massive swell. The world is fused =
together with a unifying economic system and the speed of change has accele=
rated dramatically.<br><a href=3D"http://www.universityworldnews.com/articl=
e.php?story=3D20100828205552222" style=3D"font-size: 8pt; color: #6699CC" t=
